BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Winter Global Health Club Mapathon
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260210T020000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260210T040000
DTSTAMP:20260309T062309Z
UID:c520275de0a72339@gid-seminars.wnprc.wisc.edu
CATEGORIES:Workshop
DESCRIPTION:This event is part of Love Data Week at Stanford\, an annual f
 estival highlighting topics\, opportunities and services relevant to data 
 in research. \n\nJoin us in mapping a high-priority global health project\
 , helping organizations like Doctors without Borders and the Red Cross del
 iver vital aid to at-risk communities around the world. In just 20 minutes
 \, you'll join a movement of over 100K volunteers across the world using H
 umanitarian OpenStreetMap (HOTOSM). \n\nIn our Winter Mapathon\, we’ll b
 e using satellite imagery and simple online GIS tools to trace building ou
 tlines\, creating detailed digital maps of unmapped areas. Last spring\, w
 e mapped 2084 buildings in Malawi and hope to break that record! This Wint
 er\, we’ll be mapping a high-priority global health project that helps o
 rganizations like Doctors Without Borders and the Red Cross deliver vital\
 , life-saving aid. Through Missing Maps\, these efforts are sustained in c
 ollaboration with local communities\, ensuring long-term resilience in the
  regions we map.\n\nREGISTER HERE: https://luma.com/iekdb0rh\n\nOpen to al
 l Stanford affiliates in person or over Zoom & dinner will be provided!Non
 -Stanford affiliates may join us over Zoom! \nZoom: https://stanford.zoom.
 us/j/91622371366?pwd=ytaMaENiIgaR6rnR7HScVgPwA2NpRr.1&from=addon\n\nWhat i
 s a Mapathon? Accurate maps are essential for humanitarian responses and g
 lobal health—yet many communities remain unmapped. Missing Maps is a hum
 anitarian initiative started in 2014 to address this critical gap by mappi
 ng crucial infrastructure in underrepresented areas\, often through collab
 orative “Mapathon” events. The maps created help emergency responders 
 reach communities during natural disasters\, enable healthcare workers to 
 organize vaccination campaigns\, and support NGOs in developing resilient 
 infrastructure. \n\nSo\, join us for an evening of impact on Monday Februa
 ry 9th from 6-8 pm in Branner Earth Sciences Library. No prior experience 
 is necessary—mapping is easy to learn in just 20 min\n\nEvent URL: https
 ://events.stanford.edu/event/global-health-club-mapathon-2026\n\nSource: s
 tanford_virtual
LOCATION:Mitchell Earth Sciences\, Branner Earth Sciences Library & Map Co
 llections
URL:https://events.stanford.edu/event/global-health-club-mapathon-2026
BEGIN:VALARM
ACTION:DISPLAY
DESCRIPTION:Reminder: Winter Global Health Club Mapathon
TRIGGER:-PT1H
END:VALARM
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:The Educational Impacts of School Phone Bans
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260210T200000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260210T210000
DTSTAMP:20260309T062309Z
UID:4c486e829d3d7506@gid-seminars.wnprc.wisc.edu
CATEGORIES:Lecture/Presentation/Talk
DESCRIPTION:Join the Tech Impact and Policy Center on February 10th from 1
 2PM–1PM Pacific for a seminar with Guilherme Lichand.\n\nStanford affili
 ates are invited to join us at 11:40 AM for lunch\, prior to the seminar. 
  The Winter Seminar Series continues through March\; see our Winter Semina
 r Series page for speakers and topics. Sign up for our newsletter for anno
 uncements. \n\nAbout the Seminar:\n\nA rapidly expanding literature docume
 nts the detrimental effects of excessive cell phone use\, particularly on 
 mental health outcomes and attention. While nearly all studies focus on ad
 ult populations\, many experts have used them to support phone bans in sch
 ools – partially in the hope that these might help reverse declining tre
 nds in standardized test scores dating from even before the Covid-19 pande
 mic. This paper provides first-hand evidence that phone restrictions in sc
 hools indeed causally boost K–12 learning outcomes. Leveraging the intro
 duction of a policy that banned non-pedagogical uses of cell phones within
  schools in Rio de Janeiro\, Brazil\, we contrast schools that already had
  strict rules on phone use even before the policy (the control group) to a
 ll other schools (the treatment group)\, before and after the ban. We find
  that\, 1.5 year after roll-out\, (1) the prevalence of high-usage schools
  converged across groups\; and (2) standardized test scores significantly 
 increased in treatment schools\, relative to control: in the former\, stud
 ents learned 0.06 s.d. more – enough to fully eliminate the baseline gap
  in test scores across groups.\n\nAbout the Speaker:\n\nGuilherme is an As
 sistant Professor of Education at Stanford\, co-Director at the Stanford L
 emann Center for Entrepreneurship and Educational Innovation in Brazil\, a
 nd a faculty affiliate at the Stanford King Center for Global Development\
 , the Stanford Center on Early Childhood\, the Stanford Institute for Adva
 ncing Just Societies\, and the UC Berkeley Center for Effective Global Act
 ion. He holds a PhD in Political Economy and Gove\n\nEvent URL: https://ev
 ents.stanford.edu/event/the-educational-impacts-of-school-phone-bans\n\nSo
 urce: stanford_virtual
LOCATION:Building 120\, McClatchy Hall\, Main Quad\, Studio S40 - bring yo
 ur Stanford ID card/mobile ID to enter the building
URL:https://events.stanford.edu/event/the-educational-impacts-of-school-ph
 one-bans
BEGIN:VALARM
ACTION:DISPLAY
DESCRIPTION:Reminder: The Educational Impacts of School Phone Bans
TRIGGER:-PT1H
END:VALARM
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Fighting Servants: Why Democratic Leaders Politicize Foreign Polic
 y Bureaucracies
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260210T200000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260210T211500
DTSTAMP:20260309T062309Z
UID:f39dcce95c42c363@gid-seminars.wnprc.wisc.edu
CATEGORIES:Lecture/Presentation/Talk
DESCRIPTION:About the event: Why do democratic leaders politicize foreign 
 policy bureaucracies? While existing scholarship recognizes that leaders a
 nd bureaucrats often clash\, it usually attributes these conflicts to orga
 nizational pathologies\, principal-agent problems\, or policy disagreement
 s. This project develops a theory that explains when leaders attack their 
 foreign policy bureaucracies by installing loyalists\, marginalizing or pu
 rging careerists\, and creating parallel agencies\, a strategy I call poli
 ticization. It argues that leaders tend to politicize instead of bypassing
  or coordinating with the bureaucracy when two forces come together: when 
 leaders strongly distrust the bureaucracy\, fueled by intense partisan\, i
 deological\, and social conflicts\, and have enough domestic political pow
 er to reshape institutions in their own image.\n\nAbout the speaker: Emily
  Tallo is the India-U.S. security studies postdoctoral fellow at CISAC. Sh
 e received her Ph.D. in political science from the University of Chicago i
 n August 2025. Emily’s research centers on the domestic politics of fore
 ign policy\, focusing on how leaders\, bureaucracies\, and political parti
 es shape international politics with a regional emphasis on South Asia. Be
 fore academia\, Emily was a researcher at the Henry L. Stimson Center’s 
 South Asia program in Washington\, DC\, and an editor of the online magazi
 ne South Asian Voices. Her commentary has been featured in Foreign Policy\
 , The Washington Post’s Monkey Cage blog\, and War on the Rocks.\n\nEven
 t URL: https://events.stanford.edu/event/fighting-servants-why-democratic-
 leaders-politicize-foreign-policy-bureaucracies\n\nSource: stanford_virtua
 l
LOCATION:Encina Hall\, William J. Perry Conference Room
URL:https://events.stanford.edu/event/fighting-servants-why-democratic-lea
 ders-politicize-foreign-policy-bureaucracies
BEGIN:VALARM
ACTION:DISPLAY
DESCRIPTION:Reminder: Fighting Servants: Why Democratic Leaders Politicize
  Foreign Policy Bureaucracies
TRIGGER:-PT1H
END:VALARM
END:VEVENT
